'''William George Thompson''' (January 17, 1830 &ndash; April 2, 1911) was a [[American Civil War|Civil War]] officer, trial-court judge, territorial justice, and [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Representative in the United States House of [[Iowa's 5th congressional district]].
==Biography== Thompson was born and raised in [[Butler, Pennsylvania]], the younger brother of future Pennsylvania Congressman [[John McCandless Thompson]]. In 1853, he was admitted to the [[bar (law)|bar]] and moved to [[Marion, Iowa]]. He became the prosecuting attorney for [[Linn County, Iowa]] in 1854, then left in 1856 to serve in the [[Iowa Senate]], serving until 1860. When the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] broke out he became a [[Major (United States)|major]] in the [[20th Iowa Volunteer Infantry Regiment]].
After the War, he served as district attorney for Iowa's eighth judicial district for six years. He then served briefly as [[Chief Justice]] of the [[Territory of Idaho]], from January to April 1879.
In April 1879, Thompson resigned as Chief Justice to run as a Republican to represent [[Iowa's 5th congressional district|Iowa's fifth district]] in the [[46th United States Congress|Forty-sixth Congress]], to fill the vacancy caused by the death of [[Rush Clark]]. Thompson won the special election, and served in most of the [[46th United States Congress|Forty-sixth Congress]]. In 1882, he was re-elected, serving in the [[47th United States Congress|Forty-seventh Congress]], but chose not to run in 1884 for the [[48th United States Congress|Forty-eighth]].
On his return to Iowa, Thompson served on the Marion City Council, and ran for the [[Iowa General Assembly]]. He served in the [[Iowa House of Representatives]] from 1885 to 1887. Returning to the bench, he was elected as judge of Iowa's eighteenth judicial district, serving from 1894 to 1906. He retired to [[Linn County, Iowa|Kenwood Park, Iowa]] where he died April 2, 1911. He is interred at [[Oak Shade Cemetery]] in Marion.
